originContent: _This checklist is a practical, opinionated guide for sanity-checking the writing quality, structure, and presentation of CS papers‚Äîespecially for conference (and journal) submissions. While some items are subjective, the goal is to provide concrete reminders and highlight common pitfalls. It is a living document and will continue to be updated based on feedback._
translatedContent: _This checklist is a practical, opinionated guide for sanity-checking the writing quality, structure, and presentation of CS papers‚Äîespecially for conference (and journal) submissions. originContent: ## 1. üéØ Title and Abstract
translatedContent: ## 1. üéØ Title and Abstract

originContent: - [ ] 1.1 Title is ‚â§ 15 words. Check for generic phrasing (e.g., ‚ÄúA Novel Framework...,‚Äù which conveys little information) and overly narrow focus (which may reduce the paper‚Äôs audience)‚Äîaim for concise but informative.

originContent: - [ ] 1.2 Title clearly reflects both the **problem** and the **solution**, and includes at least one technical keyword (e.g., jailbreak, OOD detection, graph learning).
translatedContent: - [ ] 1.2 Title clearly reflects both the **problem** and the **solution**, and includes at least one technical keyword (e.g., jailbreak, OOD detection, graph learning).

originContent: - [ ] 1.3 Title avoids rare or ambiguous abbreviations. Terms like LLM, AI, and ML are acceptable in CS venues, but avoid abbreviations like AD (which could refer to advertisement or anomaly detection).
translatedContent: - [ ] 1.3 Title avoids rare or ambiguous abbreviations. Terms like LLM, AI, and ML are acceptable in CS venues, but avoid abbreviations like AD (which could refer to advertisement or anomaly detection).

originContent: - [ ] 1.4 Abstract includes at least four key components: (1) problem/task definition, (2) proposed method or idea, (3) main results, and (4) broader impact or significance (some may be combined).
translatedContent: - [ ] 1.4 Abstract includes at least four key components: (1) problem/task definition, (2) proposed method or idea, (3) main results, and (4) broader impact or significance (some may be combined).

originContent: - [ ] 1.5 Abstract avoids undefined abbreviations and vague descriptors (e.g., ‚Äúimportant,‚Äù ‚Äúnovel,‚Äù ‚Äústate-of-the-art‚Äù without context).
translatedContent: - [ ] 1.5 Abstract avoids undefined abbreviations and vague descriptors (e.g., ‚Äúimportant,‚Äù ‚Äúnovel,‚Äù ‚Äústate-of-the-art‚Äù without context).

originContent: - [ ] 1.6 Bonus: Abstract includes at least one concrete, quantitative result or insight to make the work stand out. For instance, ‚Äúour method achieves 11.2√ó acceleration in test-time inference for jailbreak detection.‚Äù

originContent: ## 2. üìö Introduction

originContent: - [ ] 2.1 The main problem or task is clearly defined within the first two paragraphs.
translatedContent: - [ ] 2.1 The main problem or task is clearly defined within the first two paragraphs.

originContent: - [ ] 2.2 Motivation includes either (a) real-world use cases or (b) citations to prior work‚Äîideally both.
translatedContent: - [ ] 2.2 Motivation includes either (a) real-world use cases or (b) citations to prior work‚Äîideally both.

originContent: - [ ] 2.3 The introduction ends with a brief overview of the proposed method and its name.

originContent: - [ ] 2.4 Contributions are explicitly itemized (e.g., ‚Äú(1) first framework for ..., (2) new dataset for ..., (3) extensive evaluation on ...‚Äù).

originContent: - [ ] 2.5 Each contribution is specific and verifiable‚Äîavoid vague claims such as ‚Äúwe provide insights‚Äù or ‚Äúwe improve understanding.‚Äù

originContent: - [ ] 2.6 Bonus: Include a compelling figure on the first page‚Äîe.g., comparison to prior work, performance highlight, or visual explanation of the core idea.

originContent: - [ ] 3.1 All cited works are connected to your method, baseline, or task.
